AIM FOR THE STARS
Jefferson College Observatory Site  Join us at the Jefferson College Observatory including a site tour, training on how to read a star map, library telescope and binocular training, a meteorite exhibit, live telescope viewing, laser guided constellation tours, and previews of upcoming astronomy events of interest.

 During each event, the dome and 16-inch telescope will be used for public viewing of planets and stars. The 1,800 sq-ft observatory patio will be available to those who want to bring their own telescopes and binoculars for family viewing.

 ****All events will be held on the first Sunday evening, beginning at sunset, weather permitting. In case of inclement weather, programs will be postponed to the following month.

 2023 event dates: February 5, March 5, April 2, May 7, June 4, July 2, August 6, September 3, October 1, November 5 and December 2

 Special Eclipse Event: We will host a solar eclipse viewing event on Saturday October 14, 2023 from 10:30 am to 1:30pm

matches.description:
Paul O'Connor 
Instrumentation Scientist, Brookhaven National Laboratory

The more scientists discover about the ingredients that make up our Universe and the ways in which they evolved from a featureless gas to the systems of stars and galaxies that we see today, the more we recognize the need for new observations -- ones which can extend our reach across time and space to resolve questions at the foundations of fundamental physics. This has led to an effort within the High Energy Physics community, formerly concerned with particle accelerators to study the subatomic world, to build large facilities and instruments designed to tackle the big open questions of cosmology.

This lecture will review progress on Vera Rubin Observatory (LSST) construction, and will present several new instrument concepts for studying the physics of the early universe using the highly-redshifted radiation from atomic hydrogen which we observe in the radio frequency wavelength range.

On-site at Pace University or via Zoom. The Zoom link is on the opening page of the Westchester Amateur Astronomy web site,  www.westchesterastronomers.org .

matches.title: Ellwood School Science Night

matches.description:
Have you ever wanted to view the night sky through a telescope? And even better, learn to operate the telescope yourself? If so, you don’t want to miss this opportunity for a FREE training and telescope viewing session provided by amateur astronomers from the St. Louis Astronomical Society. 

The evening program will begin inside where it is warm and cozy with hands on training focused on teaching you and your family how to operate and use the library telescopes now available in your public library. Guests will learn how to unpack the telescope, get the telescope ready for operation, find objects in the night sky and about telescope safety issues. Using the telescope is surprisingly easy and fun for the whole family.

matches.description:
The Lake Afton Public Observatory is open to the public on Friday and Saturday nights. Some club members will set up their telescopes on the north side of the building and visitors are welcome to come observe with them. Visitors are also welcome to bring their own telescope to view with us. If you are having trouble setting up your telescope bring it with you and we would gladly help.

Under the dome of LAPO is a 16" telescope for viewing distant objects light years away or planets in our solar system. There are many displays and hands on activities to explore the outer regions of space.

Come join the Back Bay Amateur Astronomers (BBAA) for this public solar viewing event.

RSVP  here. 
Members of the public are invited to view the wonders of the universe through the telescopes of NOVAC volunteers at the Smithsonian’s Udvar-Hazy Center in Chantilly, VA. You do not need to be a member of the club or own any astronomical equipment to attend.
The event will take place on the bus parking lot of the museum. Please park your vehicle in the main visitors lot and follow signs to the observing site from the main entrance. As a reminder, parking after 4pm is free.
Shortly before sunset, feel free to inspect the different telescopes and other visual equipment on the field. Have a cosmic question? One of NOVAC’s astronomers or museum staff will be happy to help you. After sunset be prepared to enjoy the wonders of the night sky!
Don’t forget to dress appropriately for the weather. Please check the forecast. For lighting, cover a flashlight in red cellophane (the darker the better). Bring along water to keep hydrated and plan on staying the entire evening or as long as the weather allows.
Note: This outdoor event is weather-dependent and may be cancelled because of significant cloud cover or precipitation.

matches.description:
Stars on the Rock Star Party
When: Fourth Saturday of the Month, 6pm – 10pm
Where: The Park at Hickory Ridge, 1910 Walnut Ridge Drive, Rockwall, TX 75032, USA

The Texas Astronomical Society of Dallas(TAS) will be sponsoring community Star Parties in the fourth Saturday of each month weather permitting. (Exception: no event will be held in December due to the holiday activities. Star Parties will resume in January).

Each Star Party will start 30 minutes after sunset. Feel free to bring your own blankets, lawn chairs, binoculars, telescopes and dress appropriately for the weather conditions.
matches.title: Stars on the Rock Star Party

matches.description: We would love our patrons to have a chance to look at the Sun prior to the Sunday 3 PM concert. Information about the Concert: This Earth, Wind and Fire concert will focus on the earth, our community, and our diverse world with the integration of poetry. Featured pieces include the "Windstar Fanfare" by William MacDavis, Haydn's "Fire Symphony," a Virginia Beach premiere of "Stopping by Woods on a Snowy Evening" with words by Robert Frost and music by Virginia composer Catherine Fields, and a performance of Earthrise, by renown Virginia Beach composer Adolphus Hailstork featuring up to 150 singers from the Symphonicity and ODU Choruses plus a local gospel choir.

General Meeting of the Texas Astronomical Society of Dallas
University of Texas at Dallas, NOTE ROOM CHANGE FOR THIS MONTH!
We will meet in Founder's North, Room 2.102

General Meetings are held on the fourth Friday of the month (except December) and are free and open to the general public. Come join one of the oldest and largest Astronomical Societies in the Astronomical League!

matches.description:
It’s an Intergalactic, Virtual-Reality Accelerator Suit. And it’s been stolen!” Join Lt. Photeus as he tracks the sinister Captain Xenon through our solar system. “The Great Space Chase” is a detective mystery, which teaches Audiences about our solar system and the universe beyond. This astronomy program is a light-hearted look at the universe around us, and features space-related music by popular artists.

The Michigan Science Center has partnered with Laser Fantasy International to bring the world’s largest, high quality laser show library to our dome theater! Laser shows bring together art, music, science, and engineering into an entertaining experience for the whole family. MiSci will be joining dozens of theaters across the US presenting these laser show experiences.

Also, our annual Chili Night event is here again at the nature center. Prepare your best chili and come on out for an enjoyable evening of tasting many different kinds of chili. Bring your chili, place settings, and drinks, plus a dish/dessert to pass. If you are not "accomplished in the kitchen", don't worry about not bringing chili - there will be plenty on hand. 
 Telescope observing afterwards, weather permitting.This event is free and open to the public.You don't need to be a member to attend.

matches.description:
This is Ohio! Please check this calendar for cancellation, due to weather, on the date of the event.

The RAS want’s everyone to enjoy themselves, with the health and safety of everyone in attendance a priority. Wearing a mask is optional, do whatever you are comfortable with while respecting other’s personal space and please do not attend if you are not feeling well.
 
All 2022 Public Nights will be held on the first Saturday of each month, March through November. Special programs and member nights are offered on alternative weekends.
Be sure to check our events and calendar. If weather permits, there will be an opportunity to view through the big scope as well as a variety of personal scopes. If weather is cloudy, there will be a program and folks who will be happy to take you on a tour of our Observatory. We welcome all visitors! Not only will you have access to view through this magnificent scope, but our members also have a variety of telescopes to help assist you on your celestial journey. Please feel free to bring your own equipment as well.
